---
import ServiceLayout from '../../layouts/ServiceLayout.astro';

const title = 'On-demand service app development';
const description =
  'Delivery, taxi, courier and on-demand professional services apps. Real-time location, dispatch logic, in-app payments, ratings and trip history — designed and shipped by Apriori Studio.';
---

<ServiceLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  serviceType="On-demand service mobile app development"
  breadcrumbs={[
    { href: '/', label: 'Home' },
    { href: '/apps', label: 'Mobile apps' },
    { href: '/apps/on-demand', label: 'On-demand services' },
  ]}
>
  <p>
    On-demand apps — taxi, food delivery, parcel courier, on-the-spot professional services —
    look simple from the outside (request a thing, get a thing) and are quietly some of the
    most engineering-heavy apps in any category. They have to handle real-time location,
    matching algorithms, dispatch logic, payments, ratings, trip histories, support flows, and
    edge cases that only show up when something goes wrong with a delivery in the rain on a
    Saturday night. We build them with that complexity in mind from day one.
  </p>

  <h2>What we build</h2>
  <p>
    Food and grocery delivery (restaurant or store discovery, ordering, real-time tracking,
    rider dispatch). Ride-hailing apps (passenger and driver, route preview, fare estimation,
    real-time location share). Courier apps for documents and parcels (sender app + courier
    app + tracking page). Professional service marketplaces (cleaners, handymen, beauty,
    tutoring) with bookings, geofenced availability, and provider profiles. Field-service
    dispatch tools for B2B (engineers in the field, a back-office dashboard).
  </p>

  <h2>The hard parts (which we handle)</h2>

  <h3>Real-time location, done battery-efficiently</h3>
  <p>
    The biggest mistake in on-demand apps is constant high-accuracy GPS — it kills the battery
    and gets your app uninstalled. We use the right location accuracy for each part of the
    journey (low-power background tracking when the rider is on the way, high-accuracy when
    they're approaching). We respect the platform's background location rules (iOS is strict,
    Android even stricter as of recent versions), so the app keeps working when minimised
    without breaching policy.
  </p>

  <h3>Matching, dispatch and ETAs</h3>
  <p>
    The "find me the nearest available driver" logic looks easy and isn't. It needs to weigh
    distance, current load, vehicle type, customer rating, surge pricing, fairness across
    drivers, and constraints from the operator (geofences, exclusion zones, service areas). We
    build dispatch logic that's transparent and tunable — you can change the rules without
    rewriting code. ETA calculation uses a routing engine (Mapbox, Google Maps, OSRM) with
    real-time traffic.
  </p>

  <h3>Two apps (or three) sharing one backend</h3>
  <p>
    On-demand apps almost always come in pairs — customer + provider — and often a third
    operator or admin web dashboard. We design the data model and APIs once, share business
    logic, and build distinct UI for each role. Provider apps need different priorities: big
    buttons usable while moving, voice prompts, offline queue for actions taken in low-signal
    areas.
  </p>

  <h3>Payments, payouts and surge</h3>
  <p>
    Stripe Connect for split payments — customer pays, platform takes its cut, provider gets
    paid out on a schedule. Saved cards with one-tap reuse. Apple Pay and Google Pay for new
    customers. Cash payment option (still essential in some markets). Surge pricing where
    appropriate, with clear UX so customers see it before confirming. Tipping flow that
    actually gets used (defaults matter). Receipts emailed automatically.
  </p>

  <h3>Maps and routing</h3>
  <p>
    We use Google Maps SDK or Mapbox depending on cost (Google's pricing scales harshly past a
    threshold, Mapbox is cheaper at scale but has fewer features in some regions). For the
    routing engine itself: Google Directions, Mapbox Directions, or self-hosted OSRM if you're
    operating at a scale where API costs become a concern. We build the map screens to
    re-render efficiently on lower-end Android devices.
  </p>

  <h3>Push, in-app messaging and support</h3>
  <p>
    Push for status updates ("driver on the way," "arriving in two minutes," "delivered").
    In-app chat between customer and provider that auto-disables after the trip ends, with
    masked phone numbers if anonymous calling is needed (Twilio Proxy or similar). Support
    chat for issues, with proper ticketing on the back end so nothing gets lost.
  </p>

  <h3>Cancellations, refunds and dispute resolution</h3>
  <p>
    Cancellation policies that vary by stage of the trip. Automatic refunds where appropriate.
    Manual review queues for escalations. Photo-evidence flows for disputed deliveries. We
    build the operator dashboard with the queries you'll actually need, not generic "view all
    trips" lists.
  </p>

  <h3>Ratings, reviews and quality control</h3>
  <p>
    Two-way ratings (customer rates provider, provider rates customer). Automated quality
    flags for low-rated providers. Review moderation queue. Public-facing rating display done
    in a way that's fair to providers (recent ratings weighted, single bad reviews
    contextualised).
  </p>

  <h2>Compliance</h2>
  <p>
    On-demand apps touch a lot of regulation: data protection (GDPR for UK/EU operations),
    payment regulations (PSD2, Strong Customer Authentication), tax (VAT on commission), and
    sector-specific rules (food safety for delivery, taxi licensing for ride-hailing, gig-work
    employment status for providers). We don't give legal advice but we build the technical
    parts that compliance requires — audit logs, data export and deletion, age verification
    where applicable, identity verification (Stripe Identity or Onfido) for providers.
  </p>

  <h2>What it costs</h2>
  <p>
    A two-app on-demand MVP (customer + provider, basic dispatch, Stripe payments, push) starts
    at £45,000. A full operating platform with operator dashboard, surge pricing, multi-region
    support, and integrated identity verification runs £80,000 and up. Map and SMS service
    costs are usage-based and billed to you directly. Apple Developer and Google Play
    accounts are required (we can submit under yours).
  </p>

  <h2>Timeline</h2>
  <p>
    MVP for a single region with one service type: sixteen to twenty-four weeks. Multi-region,
    multi-service-type platforms take longer and benefit from a phased rollout (one region at
    a time). We share working builds every two weeks via TestFlight and Play Console.
  </p>
</ServiceLayout>
